  "slug": "french-onion-soup",
  "title": "French Onion Soup",
  "subtitle": "The kind of dinner that cooks itself.",
  "excerpt": "French Onion Soup. A slow-cooker dish that does its own work, set it in the morning, serve it at dinner.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "From Rebecca's personal cookbook. The dish sits in the classical French slow-cook tradition, associated with the Auvergne region. French cookery writers including Escoffier and the Larousse Gastronomique codified the method; cooks like Elizabeth David and Julia Child brought it into the English-language kitchen.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "French onion soup is beef broth enriched with deeply caramelised onions, served with a toasted baguette slice and melted cheese floating on top. The onions take the longest: sliced about 6 mm thick, cooked slowly in butter until they turn soft, sweet, and mahogany brown. That caramelisation is where the flavour lives.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A slow cooker does the onion stage without any stirring. Start them in the morning and finish the soup on the hob at dinner. Use more onions than seems sensible: they shrink to about a quarter of their raw volume as the water cooks out.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
