      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Caramelise the onions (slow cooker method)",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Slice the onions about 6 mm thick. They shrink down considerably, so do not cut thinner or they will become stringy.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Melt 4 tablespoons of the butter in the slow cooker. Add the onions and toss well to coat. Cook on low for 10 hours.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "After 10 hours, transfer the onions to a large saucepan on the hob. Add the remaining 2 tablespoons of butter and cook over medium-high heat for 10 to 15 minutes, stirring often, until the onions are richly brown and very sweet. This finishing step on the hob completes the caramelisation.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the soup",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "When the onions are nearly done, sprinkle flour over them and stir for 2 minutes. Add any remaining wine and increase the heat to medium-high, tossing the onions frequently until very well browned.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Reduce heat to medium. Pour in the white wine and cook for 2 to 3 minutes. Add the {{stock-beef}} of beef stock, {{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock, {{worcestershire-sauce}} of Worcestershire sauce, bay leaves, and thyme.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Simmer over medium heat for 45 minutes with the lid cracked. Remove the bay leaves and thyme stems. Season to taste with salt and pepper.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Toast the bread and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Heat the oven to 180°C (160°C fan). Slice the baguette into slices about 1 cm thick. Brush the tops with olive oil and bake for 5 minutes.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Increase the oven to 230°C (210°C fan). Top each baguette slice with a piece of {{gruyere}} and bake until the cheese melts and begins to bubble and brown.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Ladle the soup into bowls and float the warm cheese toasts on top.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add salt a pinch at a time, tasting. If still flat, finish with a squeeze of lemon or a splash of vinegar to lift it.",
              "cause": "Underseasoned, or the onions were not caramelised long enough.",
              "symptom": "The soup tastes flat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Loosen with hot stock or water, a ladle at a time, until it pours from the spoon in a ribbon.",
              "cause": "Reduced too far.",
              "symptom": "Soup is too thick"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Simmer uncovered to reduce for another 10 to 15 minutes.",
              "cause": "Stock-to-onion ratio too high.",
              "symptom": "Soup is too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Keep stirring and scraping the base as the onions caramelise. Add a splash of wine to lift any dark residue; use it to deglaze rather than discard.",
              "cause": "Heat too high or left unattended too long at the hob stage.",
              "symptom": "Onions caught and turned bitter"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Vegetarian: use vegetable stock in place of beef and chicken stock. The flavour will be lighter but the caramelised onions still carry the dish.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Smokier finish: stir in a teaspoon of smoked paprika at the end.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The soup keeps well. Make it a day ahead; the flavour deepens overnight in the fridge. Reheat gently on the hob and make the cheese toasts fresh. Freezes for up to 3 months without the bread.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "French onion soup is a dish of patience and economy: cheap onions transformed by slow heat into something deeply savoury. It is found across France but associated particularly with Lyon and the Auvergne, where hearty long-cooked soups are a staple of winter cooking. The version served in Parisian brasseries, with its thick cap of melted cheese over the bowl, is what most people picture.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
